 by officers. Unlike the metropolitan variant, imperial policing was never a simple matter of law enforcement but instead engaged in the defense of racial hegemony and empire. Officers and gendarmes waged a constant struggle against escalating banditry, the assault and murder of settlers, and nationalist politics—anticolonial violence that rejected French rule. Thus, policing became synonymous with repression, and its brutal tactics foreshadowed the torture and murder used during the War of Independence. To understand the mechanics of empire, Kalman argues that it was the first line of defense for imperial hegemony. Law, Order, and Empire outlines not only how failings in policing were responsible for decolonization in Algeria but also how torture, massacres, and "idian colonial violence—introduced from the very beginning of French policing in Algeria—created state-directed aggression from 1870 onward.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aCriminal justice, Administration ofzAlgeriaxHistoryy19th century. 0aCriminal justice, Administration ofzAlgeriaxHistoryy20th century. 0aDiscrimination in criminal justice administrationzAlgeria. 4aAFRICAN HIST & DIASPORA. 4aWEST EUROPEAN HISTORY. 7aHISTORY / Africa / North.2bisacsh  aAlgerian War of Independence, Arabs, Berbers, army mobilization, racial hegemony, anticolonialism, political violence, French rule.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311075184040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501774065?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501774065423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501774065/original  a978-3-11-075184-0  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles